# Why: Upstream draws each audit-log event as a bordered card with a
#      header section, divider line, and a 2-row meta block including
#      a multi-line User Agent string. For our typical envelope flow
#      (~25-30 events: created, sent, viewed×N, signed×N, completed,
#      etc.), this consumes 4-5 PDF pages in the appended audit log.
#      Operationally fine; visually feels inflated and harder to scan
#      at a glance — every legal-flavor doc reviewer expects denser
#      audit trails (DocuSign's is ~12 events/page; ours was ~3).
#
#      New layout (per row):
#        Line 1: [dot] EVENT_TYPE — Description.... 2026-05-08 04:05 UTC
#        Line 2:        user@email · 69.132.246.203 · Mac · Chrome 147
#        thin gray separator
#
#      All upstream fields preserved (type, description, timestamp,
#      email, IP, user agent — UA decomposed to OS + browser instead
#      of full string for compactness). Drop the bordered card and
#      vertical labels in favor of a denser two-line layout. Result:
#      ~12-15 events per page vs ~3, so a 30-event envelope fits in
#      ~2-3 pages instead of 8-10.
#
# Why-not-additive: render-audit-logs.ts is upstream. The renderRow
#      function is called by the page-grouping logic that follows;
#      replacing it changes the visual output but not the contract.
#
# Upstream-merge-fragility: MEDIUM
#      Replaces ~130 lines of renderRow body. If upstream restyles
#      the audit log (likely as Documenso evolves), this patch will
#      conflict. Easiest re-application: re-derive the compact layout
#      from the new upstream renderRow shape.
#
# Files patched:
#   - packages/lib/server-only/pdf/render-audit-logs.ts (renderRow)

